{{use dmy dates|date=July 2017}} [[File:ESP 044675 2580 RED.jpg |thumb|350px|The Hagal dune field. Image was taken on 6 February 2016 at 15:16 local Mars time.<ref name="NASA"/><ref name="IFLSCIENCE">{{cite news|last=Hale|first=Tom|date=11 July 2016|title=NASA Has Found A "Morse Code Message" On The Surface Of Mars|url=http://www.iflscience.com/space/nasa-has-found-a-morse-code-message-on-the-surface-of-mars/|publisher=IFLSCIENCE!|accessdate=19 July 2017}}</ref>]] '''Hagal''' is the informal name of a [[dune field]] on [[Mars]] located below the [[Planum Boreum|north pole of Mars]].<ref name="Time magazine"/><ref name="Icarus"/> Its name derives from the sand dunes in [[Frank Herbert]]'s novel ''[[Dune (novel)|Dune]]'' and the fictional planet [[Hagal (Dune)|Hagal]].<ref name="Icarus">{{cite journal|author1=C.J. Hansen |author2=S. Byrne |author3=G. Portyankina |author4=M. Bourke |author5=C. Dundas |author6=A. McEwen |author7=M. Mellon |author8=A. Pommerol |author9=N. Thomas|year=2013|title=Observations of the northern seasonal polar cap on Mars: I. Spring sublimation activity and processes|journal=[[Icarus (journal)|Icarus]]|issue=225|pages=881–897|url=http://www.lpl.arizona.edu/~shane/publications/hansen_etal_icarus_2013.pdf|publisher=[[Elsevier]]|quote = Please see note at Table 1 page 883: Table 1 Sites imaged systematically by HiRISE in study year 3 (MY31) of seasonal campaign. The names are informal, some based on the sand dunes in the science fiction book ''Dune''.|accessdate=19 July 2017}}</ref> It is located at coordinates 78.0° N latitude, 84.0° E longitude, and consists of linear and round dunes with a southeast [[slipface]] orientation.<ref name="Icarus"/> It was one of the dune formations targeted for imaging by the [[HiRISE]] camera, onboard the [[Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]], at the rate of one image every six weeks. in the third year (MY31–Mars Year 31)<ref name="JGR">{{cite journal|author1=Colin M. Dundas |author2=Shane Byrne |author3=Alfred S. McEwen |author4=Michael T. Mellon |author5=Megan R. Kennedy |author6=Ingrid J. Daubar |author7=Lee Saper|date=27 January 2014|title=HiRISE observations of new impact craters exposing Martian ground ice|journal=Journal of Geophysical Research|doi=10.1002/2013JE004482|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/2013JE004482/full|quote=Six sites were discovered in the northern summer of Mars Year 29 (MY29), seven in MY30, and seven in MY31. (MY refers to the Mars calendar of Clancy et al. [2000], and this notation will be used throughout this paper; years begin at LS = 0°, the beginning of northern spring. MY32 began on 31 July 2013.)|accessdate=19 July 2017|bibcode=2014JGRE..119..109D}}</ref> of its seasonal expedition.<ref name="Icarus"/> It is also known as the "Martian Morse Code" due to the linear and rounded formations of its dunes, which have the appearance of dots and dashes.<ref name="Time magazine">{{cite news|author1=Jeffrey Kluger|title=Here's What Explains the 'Morse Code' on Mars|url=http://time.com/4402622/heres-what-explains-the-morse-code-on-mars/|publisher=[[Time magazine]]|date=12 July 2016}}</ref><ref name="NASA">{{cite web|title=Martian Morse Code|url=https://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/martian-morse-code|publisher=NASA|date= 8 July 2016}}</ref><ref name="HiRISE">{{cite web|title=Martian Morse Code ESP_045334_2580|url=https://www.uahirise.org/ESP_044675_2580|publisher=HiRISE|date=29 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="Nature World News">{{cite news|author1=Jessica F|title=Morse Code in Sand Dunes Found on Mars?|url=http://www.natureworldnews.com/articles/25094/20160712/morse-code-in-sand-dunes-found-on-mars.htm|publisher=Nature World News|date=12 July 2016|quote=NASA calls the formation the "Martian Morse Code,"}}</ref>
== Formation == [[File:ESP 045334 2580 RED.dots and dashes.jpg |thumb|300px|Detail of the dots and dashes of the dunes on 6 February 2016, at 15:16 local Mars time.<ref name="NASA"/>]]
Although normally it is possible to obtain information about the wind direction from the orientation and form of sand dunes, the complexity of shapes of the Hagal dunes makes it difficult to determine the direction of the forming winds. In the case of the Hagal dunes, it is theorised that a local circular crater, probably formed due to meteorite impact and filled with sand, has decreased the quantity of dune-forming sand; this, in turn, impacted the local topography, causing a change in wind patterns.<ref name="Time magazine"/><ref name="NASA"/> [[File:ESP 044675 2580 Hagal dune field.webm|thumb|250px|NASA video clip about the Martian Morse Code]] The linear dunes (dashes) were formed through the action of bidirectional winds, acting perpendicular to the line of the sand dune, causing a [[funnel]]ing effect directing the sand to accumulate along the linear axis of the dune. The round-shaped dunes (dots) were formed when the winds that caused the linearly-shaped accumulations were interrupted. The round dunes are classified as "[[barchan]]oid dunes". However, the exact mechanism of either formation is still unknown and this is the reason the area was chosen for imaging by the HiRISE mission.<ref name="NASA"/>
Veronica Bray, HiRISE camera targeting specialist, commented that there are similarly shaped dunes in other locations on Mars, but the Hagal field provides better images of these shapes due to the uncommon characteristics of its [[topography]]. Bray also decoded the "Morse Code" of a formation as "NEE NED ZB 6TNN DEIBEDH SIEFI EBEEE SSIEI ESEE SEEE !!".<ref name="Gizmodo">{{cite news|author1=Maddie Stone|title=There's a Secret Message Written Into the Sands of Mars|url=https://gizmodo.com/theres-a-secret-message-written-into-the-sands-of-mars-1783330309|publisher=[[Gizmodo]]|date=8 July 2016}}</ref><ref name="CNN">{{cite news|author1=Doug Criss|title=Message from Mars? Morse code dunes found on red planet|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/07/12/health/mars-morse-code-trnd/index.html|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=13 July 2016}}</ref> {{clear}}
