{{Infobox mountain | name = Mount Hillaby | photo = | photo_caption = | elevation_m = 340 | elevation_ref = | prominence_m = 340 | prominence_ref = <ref name=pb>[http://www.peakbagger.com/peak.aspx?pid=8267 Peakbagger]</ref> | map = Barbados | map_caption = | label_position = | listing = [[List of countries by highest point|Country high point]] | location = [[Barbados]], [[Caribbean]] | range = | coordinates = {{coord|13.2105|N|59.5818|W|type:mountain_region:BB-02_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | range_coordinates = | coordinates_ref = | topo = | type = | age = | last_eruption = | first_ascent = | easiest_route = }}
The peak of '''Mount Hillaby''' is the highest point on the Eastern [[Caribbean]] island of [[Barbados]]. The peak is located in the [[parish]] of [[Saint Andrew, Barbados|Saint Andrew]]. It immediately overlooks the area known as the Scotland District to the north and east which comprises geologically old sediments prone to erosion.<ref>[http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1993/ UNESCO: The Scotland District of Barbados - UNESCO World Heritage Centre]</ref><ref name="Carrington, Sean 2007 25">{{cite book |author=Carrington, Sean |title=A~Z of Barbados Heritage |year=2007 |publisher=Macmillan Caribbean Publishers Limited|page=25 |isbn=0-333-92068-6}}</ref>
==References== {{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->
==External links== *[http://whc.unesco.org/pg_friendly_print.cfm?cid=326&id=1993& Mount Hillaby & the Scotland District] - The UNESCO World Heritage Centre website
